Arun Chavan

Started: 2021-03-11

1 Background

Here we perform clustering of the amphioxus data based on parameters that we detemined according to tests in 05a_clustering_test-parameters.Rmd. We will use:

  1. All genes
  2. SCTransform normalization
  3. Leiden clustering

7.4 Tissue contribution

What fraction of cells in each cluster come from which tissue?

# Arrange clusters by tissue with max cell contribution and use the order as factor levels for plotting
clust_lvls <- bf@meta.data %>%
  group_by(cluster, orig.ident) %>%
  tally() %>%
  ungroup() %>%
  group_by(cluster) %>%
  mutate(percent = n*100/sum(n)) %>%
  ungroup() %>%
  select(-n) %>%
  pivot_wider(names_from = "orig.ident", values_from = "percent") %>%
  mutate(max_tissue = apply(., MARGIN = 1, FUN = which.max)) %>% 
  mutate(max_tissue = case_when(max_tissue == 2 ~ "phar",
                                max_tissue == 3 ~ "mdiv",
                                max_tissue == 4 ~ "hgut")) %>% 
  arrange(max_tissue) %>% 
  mutate(cluster = fct_inorder(cluster)) %>%
  pull(cluster)

# tissue contribution in percent cells
tissue_contrib_pct <- bf@meta.data %>% 
  group_by(cluster, orig.ident) %>% 
  tally() %>% 
  ungroup() %>% 
  group_by(cluster) %>% 
  mutate(percent_cells = n*100/sum(n)) %>% 
  ungroup() %>% 
  mutate(cluster = factor(cluster, levels = clust_lvls)) %>% 
  ggplot(aes(percent_cells, cluster, fill = orig.ident)) +
  geom_col() +
  theme_half_open_grid()

# tissue contribution in number of cells
tissue_contrib_n <- bf@meta.data %>% 
  group_by(cluster, orig.ident) %>% 
  tally() %>% 
  ungroup() %>% 
  mutate(cluster = factor(cluster, levels = clust_lvls)) %>% 
  ggplot(aes(n, cluster, fill = orig.ident)) +
  geom_col() +
  labs(x = "n_cells") +
  theme_half_open_grid()

tissue_contrib <- tissue_contrib_n + tissue_contrib_pct + plot_layout(guides = "collect")

ggsave(here(basedir, "results/05b_clustering/tissue-contribution_pct-and-n-cells.pdf"),

7.5 Correlations between clusters

# calculate average gene expression
avg.exp <- AverageExpression(bf, 
                             assays = "SCT", 
                             slot = "scale.data", 
                             features = VariableFeatures(bf), 
                             return.seurat = FALSE, verbose = FALSE) %>% 
  .[["SCT"]] %>% 
  as.data.frame()

# build correlation matrix from expression data
cormat <- cor(avg.exp, method = 'pearson')

# hclust for reordering clusters in plot
dd <- as.dist((1 - cormat)) 
hc <- hclust(dd, method = 'complete')

# melt 
cormat.tidy <- cormat %>% 
  as.data.frame() %>% 
  rownames_to_column(var = "v1") %>% 
  pivot_longer(
    cols = where(is.numeric),
    names_to = "v2",
    values_to = "corr"
  ) %>% 
  mutate(v1 = factor(v1, levels = hc$labels[hc$order]),
         v2 = factor(v2, levels = hc$labels[hc$order]))

# plot
p.cormat <- ggplot(data = cormat.tidy,
                   aes(v1, v2, fill = corr, label = round(corr, 2))) +
  geom_tile(colour = "white") +
  scale_fill_gradient2(
    low = pal_okabe[5],
    mid = "White",
    high = pal_okabe[6],
    midpoint = 0,
    name = "Correlation",
    guide = guide_colorbar(barheight = unit(8, "char"))
  ) +
  coord_fixed(ratio = 1) +
  labs(caption = "Pearson correlation using SCT residuals") +
  theme_tileplot(font_size = 10)

ggsave(here(basedir, "results/05b_clustering/cormatrix_avg-exp.pdf"),
       p.cormat, width = 7, height = 6, units = "in", device = cairo_pdf)

8 Marker genes

To reduce the numnber of comparisons, we will use only expressed genes, which we here define as genes that have non-zero expression in at least one cluster (according to averaged expression). Technically this may be a superfluous filtering step given that FindAllMarkers() by default only tests genes that are expressed in at least 10% of the cells in the cluster.

8.1 List of expressed genes

First, we calculate average gene expression. Note that when return.seurat = FALSE, the returned values are not log-normalized, so we have to log normalize them.

bf.avg <- AverageExpression(bf, slot = "data", return.seurat = FALSE, verbose = FALSE) %>% 
  map(.f = log1p)
genes.expressed <- names(which(rowSums(bf.avg$RNA) != 0))

8.2 Detect

markers.raw <- FindAllMarkers(bf, 
                              assay = "RNA", 
                              features = genes.expressed, 
                              logfc.threshold = 0, 
                              return.thresh = 1, 
                              base = 2, 
                              verbose = FALSE)
# save unfiltered output
write_csv(markers.raw, here(basedir, "results/05b_clustering/files/markers_raw-output.csv"))

8.3 BH correction

Seurat, by default, uses Bonferroni correction. Since that is too conservative, we will use Benjamini-Hochberg corrected p-values instead. There is no option to change the p.adjust method in FindAllMarkers(), so we just have to correct them after running FindAllMarkers(). In order for us to be able to run BH correction, we need FindAllMarkers() to report p-values for all genes, unfiltered by logFC threshold or p value threshol, since its not appropriate to run BH correction on a subset of pvalues. For this reason, we have set logfc.threshold = 0 and return.thresh = 1 in the FindAllMarkers() call above.

# nest
markers <- markers.raw %>% 
  group_by(cluster) %>% 
  nest() %>% 
  ungroup()
markers$data <- map(.x = markers$data, 
                    .f = function(x) {
                      mutate(x, pval_BH = p.adjust(p = p_val, method = "BH"))
                    })

8.4 Filter

# filter 
markers$data <- markers$data %>% 
  map(.f = function(x) {
    filter(x,
           pval_BH < 0.05, 
           avg_log2FC > 0.25)
  })
write_csv(unnest(markers, cols = data), 
          here(basedir, "results/05b_clustering/files/markers_filtered.csv"))

nmarkers.dotplot <- markers %>%
